value.value: The series of molecular signals initiated by the binding of the cell surface receptor CD27 to its physiological ligand CD70, and ending with the regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.
Catalysis of the reaction: H+ + NADPH + S-nitrosoglutathione = NADP+ + S-(hydroxysulfenamide)glutathione.
Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of chromatin looping.

The process of regulating the proliferation and elimination of CD8-positive alpha-beta T cells such that the total number of CD8-positive alpha-beta T cells within a whole or part of an organism is stable over time in the absence of an outside stimulus.

Catalysis of the reaction: 2-oxoadipate + H+ + N(6)-[(R)-lipoyl]-L-lysyl-[dihydrolipoyllysine-residue succinyltransferase] = CO2 + N(6)-[(R)-S(8)-glutaryldihydrolipoyl]-L-lysyl-[dihydrolipoyllysine-residue succinyltransferase].

A multi-enzyme complex that catalyzes the oxidative decarboxylation of 2-oxoadipate to glutaryl-CoA, thereby acting in the final step of lysine and tryptophan catabolism in mitochondria. The complex comprises multiple copies of three enzymes referred to as E1, E2 and E3: 2-oxoadipate dehydrogenase (E1), dihydrolipoamide S-succinyltransferase (E2) and dihydrolipoamide dehydrogenase (E3).

definition.value: The catalytic activities of the individual components of this complex are represented by the molecular function terms '2-oxoadipate dehydrogenase activity ; GO:0160166' (E1), 'dihydrolipoyllysine-residue succinyltransferase activity ; GO:0004149' (E2), and 'dihydrolipoyl dehydrogenase activity ; GO:0004148' (E3).

value.value: The protein coat that surrounds the infective nucleic acid in some virus particles where the subunits (capsomeres) are arranged to form an icosahedron with T=9 symmetry. The T=9 capsid is composed of 12 pentameric and 80 hexameric capsomeres.
The protein coat that surrounds the infective nucleic acid in some virus particles where the subunits (capsomeres) are arranged to form an icosahedron with T=21 or pseudo T=21 symmetry.
The protein coat that surrounds the infective nucleic acid in some virus particles where the subunits (capsomeres) are arranged to form an icosahedron with T=27 or pseudo T=27 symmetry.
The protein coat that surrounds the infective nucleic acid in some virus particles where the subunits (capsomeres) are arranged to form an icosahedron with T=28 symmetry.
The protein coat that surrounds the infective nucleic acid in some virus particles where the subunits (capsomeres) are arranged to form an icosahedron with T=31 or pseudo T=31 symmetry.
Enables the transfer of histamine from one side of a membrane to the other.
A cellular developmental process by which the outer layer of the cell (the cortex) rotates relative to the inner cytoplasm.

label.value: somatic muscle attachment to chitin-based cuticle

value.value: The developmental process in which a somatic muscle attaches to the chitin-based cuticle. In insects, this may occur via a specialized epithelial cell adherence to the chitinous extracellular matrix and to muscle cells through their basement membrane.

label.value: magnesium ion transport from cytosol to endoplasmic reticulum

value.value: The directed movement of magnesium ion from cytosol to endoplasmic reticulum.
Any process that activates or increases the rate which autophagosomes fuse with a vacuole (yeast) or lysosome (e.g. mammals and insects).
Catalysis of the transport of a dipeptide across a membrane; transport is independent of the movement of any other molecular species.
A process in which iron is taken up from the contents of the intestine.
The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of piperine.
Catalysis of the reaction: a quinol + nitrate = a quinone + H2O + nitrite.
The binding activity of a molecule that brings together a target membrane and an autophagosome during autophagy.
The directed movement of substance through the space in between adjacent cells, rather than through the cells themselves.
Binds to and increases the activity of the enzyme phospholipase C.
Binds to and stops, prevents or reduces the activity of the enzyme phospholipase C.
Enables size- and charge-selective transport of solutes through a tight junction barrier paracellularly, across the epithelium.
An organelle membrane contact site between peroxisomal membrane and mitochondrial outer membrane.
The binding activity of a molecule that brings together the peroxisome and the mitochondrial outer membrane, establishing the localization of the peroxisome close to the mitochondrion.

Catalysis of the reaction: a C28-steroid + O2 + reduced NADPH--hemoprotein reductase = a (22S)-22-hydroxy C28-steroid + H+ + H2O + oxidized NADPH--hemoprotein reductase. Also catalyzes the C-22 hydroxylation of a variety of C27 and C29 steroids.

A process of exocytosis that uses the autophagy machinery to facilitate secretion of the cytosolic cargo such as leaderless cytosolic proteins which cannot enter the conventional secretory pathway operating via the endoplasmic reticulum and the Golgi apparatus.
Binds to and stops, prevents or reduces the activity of L-lactate dehydrogenase.
A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of a sensory hair cell stereocilium bundle.

label.value: negative regulation of phospholipase C/protein kinase C signal transduction

value.value: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of phospholipase C/protein kinase C signal transduction.
Catalysis of the reaction: ditrans,polycis-polyprenol + NAD(P) = ditrans,polycis-polyprenal+ NAD(P)H + H+.
Catalysis of the reaction: ditrans,polycis-dolichal+ H+ + NAD(P)H = ditrans,polycis-dolichol+ NAD(P).
Catalysis of the reaction: ditrans,polycis-polyprenal+ H+ + NADPH = ditrans,polycis-dolichal+ NADP.
Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of 7-methylguanosine mRNA capping.

A membrane-bounded organelle found in a microsporidian spore,  that swells with water, and exerts pressure to rupture the polar cap and evert the polar tube through which the sporoplasm escapes to infect the host.
A structural component of the microsporidian spore's invasion apparatus that is located at the anterior end of the spore and serves to attach the polar tube to the inside of the spore wall.
A protein folding process that facilitates the import of a subset of soluble proteins into mitochondrial intermembrane space via disulfide bond formation.

The binding activity of a molecule that brings together two mitochondrion membranes via membrane lipid binding or by interacting with a mitochondrial outer membrane protein, to establish or maintain the localization of the mitochondrion.

label.value: cysteine-dependent adenosine diphosphate thiazole synthase activity

value.value: Catalysis of the reaction: [ADP-thiazole synthase]-L-cysteine + glycine + NAD(+) = [ADP-thiazole synthase]-dehydroalanine + ADP-5-ethyl-4-methylthiazole-2-carboxylate + 2 H(+) + 3 H2O + nicotinamide.
Catalysis of the reaction: cytidine(32)/uridine(32) in tRNA + S-adenosyl-L-methionine = 2'-O-methylcytidine(32)/2'-O-methyluridine(32) in tRNA + H+ + S-adenosyl-L-homocysteine.

label.value: positive regulation of androgen receptor signaling pathway

value.value: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of androgen receptor signaling.

A Golgi-derived organelle that forms in primary spermatocytes during spermatogenesis of some nematodes including C. elegans. This 'double organelle' consists of a fibrous body containing major sperm protein and a membranous organelle that envelops the developing fibrous body.

A protein-containing complex that contains the fragile X mental retardation protein (FMRP) and cytoplasmic FMRP Interacting protein 1 (CYIFIP1), and is capable of inhibiting translation initiation by binding to the eIF4F complex.
Catalysis of the reaction: L-serine + succinyl-CoA = CoA + O-succinyl-L-serine.
Any of the lipid bilayers that surround an apicoplast and form the apicoplast envelope.
Enables the transfer of ergothioneine from one side of a membrane to the other.
A sodium-specific negative tropism that is crucial for surviving and thriving under high salinity.
Enables the transfer of heme B from one side of a membrane to the other.
